File: public\ESP32Codes\PlatformIO\02_Audio_Haptics\Haxel\HAL_SPEC.md:205
Line: Continuous 8-bit amplitude register. `write(0, v)` maps `v` → 0..127 (LRA) or 0..255 (ERM unsigned), written to register `0x02`. This is how arbitrary patterns ride through — including audio-reactive.

File: public\ESP32Codes\PlatformIO\02_Audio_Haptics\Haxel\HAL_SPEC.md:208
Line: Patterns that opt in to "use on-chip library" call `Pattern::triggerOnChip(effectId)` which the HAL maps to the waveform sequencer (reg `0x04..0x0B`) + Go (`0x0C |= 0x01`). Used by patterns like `BuzzClick`, `Notification`, `SharpDouble` — see [PATTERN_LIBRARY.md](PATTERN_LIBRARY.md).

File: public\ESP32Codes\PlatformIO\02_Audio_Haptics\Haxel\HAL_SPEC.md:255
Line: > **You are responsible for flyback protection.** Coils without a Schottky diode across them will fly the gate driver of your MOSFET and possibly your ESP32 GPIO. Inspect your wiring before powering up. Haxel writes a 1 Hz, 30 % heartbeat for the first 5 seconds — listen and feel that the actuator is alive and stable before continuing.

