File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:3
Line: **Submitted in support of:** NEA Research Grants in the Arts Application #1949260 — CymaSpace, "Universal Music Design Curriculum" project (PI Nate Hergert, Project Director Shawn Trail, PhD).

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:5
Line: **Subject:** Curricular efficacy supplement — pre-pilot evidence that a Deaf-centered STEAM music curriculum, hosted on the CyberDeck and grounded in the Sonic Agency framework, will produce measurable improvements in K-12 DHH student engagement, learning, and creative expression.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:12
Line: This supplement documents the curricular foundation that the NEA-funded research will validate. Phase 1 of the grant (Jan–Jun 2026) explicitly calls for the concurrent development of laboratory perception studies and a learning-module prototype. Twelve detailed lesson plans, a K-12 scope-and-sequence, a research audit, and a hardware-software technical specification have been authored against the four NEA research questions and the project's three goals. The curriculum operationalizes Brandon LaBelle's *sonic agency* construct through three Deaf-led practices identified in the ASSETS 2025 group autoethnography ("Sonic Agency," Cavdir et al.): bespoke design, hacking-as-resilience, and performance-as-visibility. Where prior accessibility work has framed DHH learners as recipients, this curriculum frames them as composers, engineers, and publishers. The CyberDeck — a rugged, field-deployable, off-grid hub — gives that framing teeth. We argue below that the pedagogical design is positioned to deliver the qualitative and quantitative signals the NEA's mixed-methods evaluation requires.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:18
Line: ### RQ1 — What educational tools can be developed to increase multi-sensory music education in K-12 settings?

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:22
Line: The first class is the **CyberDeck hub**. It is the "omnivorous black box" Simeone described in the CyberDeck residency application — a portable computer that runs off solar, thermoelectric, handcrank, or scavenged DC. Its pedagogical value is not portability for its own sake; it is the fact that Deaf schools, often without dedicated music rooms or treated studios, can deploy a curriculum unit anywhere with no infrastructure assumptions. Hergert's reflection in the autoethnography that "many Deaf schools don't have a music program" (Sonic Agency, §5.1.1) is the design constraint the CyberDeck answers directly.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:24
Line: The second class is **wearable interfaces**: the PULSE haptic vest and the GestoLumina (GeLu) wristware. Both have NIME-published pedigrees and are already proven in mixed-hearing performance (NIME 2024 paper; ASSETS 2025 case study, §4). The curriculum requires nothing new at the hardware level — it requires a teachable scaffolding around what already works.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:30
Line: ### RQ2 — What are DHH student perceptions of their multisensory musical experiences of a haptic curricular prototype?

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:34
Line: Within Band 1, LP-01 establishes a perceptual baseline — students learn to sign FAST, SLOW, LOUD, QUIET in response to vibrotactile pulses. LP-03 introduces frequency-to-color mapping; students predict and report the color of an unseen sound source. LP-04 (Stem-to-Body Mapping) gives every student a direct opportunity to articulate why a particular instrument *should* live on a particular body zone — which is exactly the qualitative signal the NEA's data analysis plan codes for. The articulation is not a side effect; it is the assignment.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:36
Line: The autoethnography's most poignant audience reaction — DS reporting that Deaf-school students who tried the vest said "they could actually feel things, instead of white noise from many musical instruments getting mixed up" (§5.1.1) — is the perception we hypothesize will recur in classroom pilots. LP-04's design makes that hypothesis falsifiable: if students cannot distinguish stems by feel, the field-note protocol will catch it; if they can, the saved mapping diagrams document it.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:38
Line: ### RQ3 — What are DHH students' attitudes toward the use of the haptic curricular prototype?

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:42
Line: The second is the capstone artist statement in LP-12. Students frame their final composition within sonic-agency theory, citing LaBelle directly. The grant's qualitative-coding plan (NEA pp. 12-14) can mine these statements for evidence of identity-claims, ownership-claims, and critique — the markers that distinguish a learner who has internalized the framework from one who has tolerated it.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:44
Line: The third is voluntary participation. The Mixed-Hearing Protocol described in the curriculum map asks hearing peers to wear the vest blindfolded and identify instruments — recasting the DHH learner, who is already fluent in this perceptual mode, as the expert in the room. We expect this role inversion to generate the kind of attitudinal data that the grant's interview protocols are designed to elicit: confidence, ownership, leadership.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:46
Line: ### RQ4 — Does a multi-sensory haptic curriculum improve music knowledge and understanding for K-12 DHH students?

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:60
Line: The curriculum architecture is designed to be *informed by* Phase 1 lab findings and *deployable in* Phase 2 classroom pilots without redesign. The four pedagogical pillars — body before notation, see-and-feel before hear, sign-compatible expression, and DHH-as-designer — are the curriculum's load-bearing structure; the specific mappings, palettes, and class lists within each lesson are intentionally configurable. When OHSU's Reiss Lab reports an optimal CI filterbank, the Motion-to-Synth audio engine's CI-friendly preset is the file that gets updated, not the entire syllabus. When Telegraph Mastering's perceptual tests identify the most discriminable haptic frequency ranges, the PULSE channel routing in LP-04 is the file that gets updated. The curriculum is engineered to absorb Phase 1's findings, not to be invalidated by them.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:62
Line: For the social-outcomes goal, the curriculum's mixed-hearing protocol and family share-nights (described in `CURRICULUM_MAP.md`) directly produce the observational data NEA needs. Hearing peers wearing vests and identifying stems blindly is observable, recordable, and codeable. The choice to seat the hearing learner in the *novice* position is itself a social outcome — the curriculum changes who is the expert in the room.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:68
Line: The NEA application commits to a qualitative-triangulation methodology (surveys + field notes + interview transcripts) with emergent coding and inductive thematic analysis modeled after Braun & Clarke (NEA p. 10). The curriculum produces artifacts at every grain — drawn pictures (K-2), saved score files (3-5), recorded loop and `.map` files (6-8), git pull-requests and trained `.onnx` models (9-12). Each is timestamped, anonymizable, and stored locally on the CyberDeck under encrypted per-student partitions (see `TECHNICAL_SPEC.md` §5.4), aligning with the application's data-security commitments (NEA pp. 16-17).

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:90
Line: This strategy serves two NEA-relevant ends. First, it makes scaling beyond Oregon trivial — a teacher in Tennessee or Texas can build a CyberDeck from the BOM and run the curriculum without proprietary purchases. Second, it positions the project to seed the *next* generation of DHH music technologists. Goodman et al. (Sonic Agency ref [31, 32]) and the broader literature flagged the lack of DHH designers as a primary access barrier. Open-source release of student-modifiable code, combined with the LP-10 / LP-11 design-engineering progression, is the curriculum's contribution to closing that gap.

File: public\Projects\DHHCurriculum\GRANT_ALIGNMENT.md:98
Line: — End of supplement.

