File: public\Projects\LibraryOfBabel\BLUEPRINT_REPOSITORY\chillblast-freezer\ARCHITECTURE.md:185
Line: The mitt cannot speak ASL back, so received messages from peers/supervisor are encoded as **paired LRA patterns** across LRA2 + LRA3. A pattern is a 4-pulse sequence at 175 Hz where each pulse is either L2-only, L3-only, both, or neither, giving 4^4 = 256 distinguishable patterns — more than enough for the 20-word vocabulary + meta-commands. Workers receive a printed pocket card during onboarding; muscle memory builds within 1–2 shifts per field trials at silent-siren-industrial precursor.

File: public\Projects\LibraryOfBabel\BLUEPRINT_REPOSITORY\chillblast-freezer\ARCHITECTURE.md:187
Line: LRA1 (pinky-edge) is reserved for "incoming message — pay attention." LRA4 (cuff radial) is reserved for frostbite/priority alerts only — never used for vocabulary, so its meaning is unambiguous.

